\subsection{Summary of Comparative Findings}
\label{subsec:comp_summary}

The comparative analysis yields five principal findings:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{No single passive non-invasive method is universally optimal.} AE provides the earliest and most sensitive detection of starvation and covers a wider fault type range than vibration or ultrasound alone, but imposes the highest data-rate requirement. Vibration is the most mature and widely deployed, but is limited in frequency range for early lubrication fault detection. Passive ultrasound occupies a middle position: higher frequency range than vibration, lower than AE, and already industrially deployed -- albeit with simple threshold processing.
    \item \textbf{Signal processing sophistication is not yet matched by deployment maturity.} The most diagnostically capable SP approaches (kappa regression, GNN fusion) remain at the research stage. The field's industrial deployment is dominated by methods from the 2000s or earlier.
    \item \textbf{Active and invasive methods provide quantitatively superior film thickness information} at the cost of deployment barriers. They are best suited to controlled test environments or high-value assets where the installation investment is justified.
    \item \textbf{Operating condition compensation is the central SP challenge for passive methods.} Methods that explicitly target $\kappa$ or $\Lambda$ via physics-informed regression are the most principled approach, but remain at the research stage.
    \item \textbf{Contamination detection is the least well-served fault type for passive methods.} AE multi-band hit-rate is sensitive to abrasive particles specifically; no passive method provides reliable general contamination monitoring. Oil multi-parameter or magnetic methods are required for comprehensive contamination monitoring but impose invasive installation.
\end{enumerate}
